A short walktrough the data

The S&P mining data contains information on 40702 mines globally. It contains information on location of these mines, the type of mineral that is explored, and the type of technology used for mining and processing. However, not all mines have complete information on all variables.



Commodities

This is the list of commodities that are explored in the dataset. ‘n’ is the number of mines that explore each commodity, and ‘perc’ is the percentage of mines that explore each commodity. It is possible to see here that around 35 and 13% of the mines explore gold and copper, respectively.




However, some mines have more than one commodity. The table below shows the relationship between the ‘primary commodity’ and the other commodities explored in the same mine. The table is sorted by the number of mines that explore each combination of commodities.





Production Methods

The table below shows types of technology used in mining according to the dataset. As seen here, unfortunately for more than 80% of the mines, this information is not available.




The same is true for the data on processing methods, and production forms.





Operation Status

More than 54% of the mines in the dataset are inactive, for one reason or another.





These are the types of ‘development stages’ included in the dataset.





And finally, this is the full table with the combinations between ‘development stage’ and ‘operation status’.





A focus on energy transition minerals

This part of the analysis of the dataset focuses on minerals that are important for the energy transition.

These minerals are: Lithium, Cobalt, Nickel, Graphite, Rare Earth Elements, Copper, and Manganese.

First, we filter the dataset to include mines that explore these minerals more broadly, and then filter to show the mines in which these minerals are the primary commodity.





There are 40702 mines in the dataset. Of these, 13075 explore at least one of the energy transition minerals, and 8330 have one of these minerals as the primary commodity.

The table below show how many mines explore these minerals as their primary commodity.





The table below show the number of mines in which these minerals are obtained as both a primary or non-primary commodity.
